Asthe pain progresses, A-delta fibers diminish inconductivity. The result isthat
the patient looses the ability tolocalize the lesion, and becomes dependent on
the C-Type fibers ofthe paleospinalthalamic pathway'. The Neural-Scan takes
advantage ofthis mechanism bytesting A-delta fiber function inallthe major
nerves inaregion, sothesubject isher‘own control independent ofage, gender
and population data comparisons. The nerve requiring the highest amplitude to
cause impulse conduction isthe nerve associated with the nerve-root lesions
with 95% sensitivity, asshown inapublished peer-reviewed three-year study’.
Ofnote isthe main difference between SPF NCS and standard NCV/EMG
testing. The latter only test forsensory and motor function but not the pain
directly. Itiswell established that NCV/EMG, CTand MRIscans are notprimary
diagnostic method butadjunctive tothe H&P exam’. Unfortunately, H&P exam is
not very sensitive. Cork reports inher three-year study ofsevere back pain
patients, inwhich ofthe49patients studied 25were failed back surgery cases,
the patients that should bethe easiest todiagnose, the physical-neurological
exam only had 62% sensitivity inlocating thespecific nerve-root involved‘.1
